{"key":"post-10161788","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10161788</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I placed one, quite dark, little circle right in the middle (that is, the loop held a great spore mass) and each section had a nice black dot in the center with little extra water around.&amp;nbsp; But seriously, loosing 14 of 15 sections in 6 days!&amp;nbsp; I must have done something wrong. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Next time, use such a small amount of spores that you can't see them on the dish.&amp;nbsp; Don't put them in a tiny dot.&amp;nbsp; Swipe the loop back and forth as you move it from top to bottom of each section.&amp;nbsp; This spreads the spores out, so the bacteria and molds germinate separate from the mushroom spores hopefully.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;All wild prints are contaminated.&amp;nbsp; That's why we use agar.&amp;nbsp; We can isolate healthy mycelium away from the contaminants.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10209031</next>\n<prev>10161455</prev>\n<first>10161002</first>\n<last>10209031</last>\n<when>1239689663</when>\n<utime>04/14/09 09:14 AM</utime>\n</post>"}